<text top="41" left="55" width="168" height="10" font="font0" id="p1_t1" reading_order_no="0" segment_no="0" tag_type="title">Algorithms for Molecular Biology 2006, 1 :6<i>Algorithms for Molecular Biology</i></text>
<text top="41" left="415" width="139" height="10" font="font1" id="p1_t2" reading_order_no="1" segment_no="1" tag_type="text">http://www.almob.org/content/1/1/6</text>
<text top="756" left="503" width="51" height="10" font="font1" id="p1_t3" reading_order_no="112" segment_no="10" tag_type="text">Page 4 of 12<b>1</b></text>
<text top="769" left="432" width="122" height="8" font="font3" id="p1_t4" reading_order_no="113" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">(page number not for citation purposes)</text>
<text top="89" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t5" reading_order_no="2" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">alignments. Depending on the degree of similarity among</text>
<text top="107" left="55" width="106" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t6" reading_order_no="3" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">the motifs, alignment of</text>
<text top="107" left="183" width="113" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t7" reading_order_no="7" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">and M 3 may be rejected in<i>(page number not for citation purposes)</i></text>
<text top="124" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t8" reading_order_no="8" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">the greedy algorithm, so these motifs may not be aligned</text>
<text top="137" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t9" reading_order_no="9" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">in the resulting multiple alignment. It is easy to see that</text>
<text top="150" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t10" reading_order_no="10" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">the resulting multiple alignment would not only be bio-</text>
<text top="163" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t11" reading_order_no="11" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">logically questionable, but it would also obtain a numer-<i>M</i></text>
<text top="176" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t12" reading_order_no="12" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">ically lower score as it would involve only two pairwise</text>
<text top="190" left="55" width="102" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t13" reading_order_no="13" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">alignments of the motif.</text>
<text top="213" left="55" width="225" height="10" font="font7" id="p1_t14" reading_order_no="14" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">Multiple alignment with user-defined anchor</text>
<text top="224" left="55" width="31" height="10" font="font7" id="p1_t15" reading_order_no="15" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">points</text>
<text top="236" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t16" reading_order_no="16" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">To overcome the above mentioned difficulties, and to</text>
<text top="248" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t17" reading_order_no="17" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">deal with other situations that cause problems for align-</text>
<text top="259" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t18" reading_order_no="18" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">ment programs, we implemented a semi-automatic</text>
<text top="271" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t19" reading_order_no="19" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">anchored alignment approach. Here, the user can specify<i>two </i></text>
<text top="283" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t20" reading_order_no="20" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">an arbitrary number of anchoring points in order to guide</text>
<text top="295" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t21" reading_order_no="21" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">the alignment procedure. Each anchor point consists of a</text>
<text top="306" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t22" reading_order_no="22" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">pair of equal-length segments of two of the input<b>Multiple alignment with user-defined anchor </b></text>
<text top="318" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t23" reading_order_no="23" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">sequences. An anchor point is therefore characterised by<b>points</b></text>
<text top="330" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t24" reading_order_no="24" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">five coordinates: the two sequences involved, the starting</text>
<text top="342" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t25" reading_order_no="25" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">positions in these sequences and the length of the anchored</text>
<text top="353" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t26" reading_order_no="26" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">segments. As a sixth parameter, our method requires a</text>
<text top="365" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t27" reading_order_no="27" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">score that determines the priority of an anchor point. The<i>anchored </i></text>
<text top="377" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t28" reading_order_no="28" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">latter parameter is necessary, since it is in general not</text>
<text top="389" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t29" reading_order_no="29" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">meaningful to use all anchors proposed by the user. It is</text>
<text top="400" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t30" reading_order_no="30" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">possible that the selected anchor points are inconsistent<i>anchoring points </i></text>
<text top="412" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t31" reading_order_no="31" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">with each other in the sense that they cannot be included</text>
<text top="424" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t32" reading_order_no="32" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">in one single multiple output alignment, see [16] for our</text>
<text top="436" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t33" reading_order_no="33" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">concept of consistency. Thus, it may be necessary for the</text>
<text top="447" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t34" reading_order_no="34" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">algorithm to select a suitable subset of the proposed</text>
<text top="459" left="55" width="61" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t35" reading_order_no="35" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">anchor points.</text>
<text top="483" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t36" reading_order_no="36" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">Our software provides two slightly different options for<i>sequences </i></text>
<text top="494" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t37" reading_order_no="37" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">using anchor points. There is a strong anchoring option,</text>
<text top="506" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t38" reading_order_no="38" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">where the specified anchor positions are necessarily<i>starting</i></text>
<text top="518" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t39" reading_order_no="39" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">aligned to each other, consistency provided. The remain-<i>positions </i></text>
<text top="530" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t40" reading_order_no="40" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">der of the sequences is then aligned based on the consist-</text>
<text top="541" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t41" reading_order_no="41" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">ency constraints given by these pre-aligned positions. This<i>length </i></text>
<text top="553" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t42" reading_order_no="42" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">option can be used to enforce correct alignment of those</text>
<text top="565" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t43" reading_order_no="43" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">parts of the sequences for which additional expert infor-</text>
<text top="577" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t44" reading_order_no="44" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">mation is available. For example, we are planning to align<i>score </i></text>
<text top="588" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t45" reading_order_no="45" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">RNA sequences by using both primary and secondary</text>
<text top="600" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t46" reading_order_no="46" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">structure information. Here, locally conserved secondary<i>priority </i></text>
<text top="612" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t47" reading_order_no="47" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">structures could be used as 'strong' anchor points to make</text>
<text top="624" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t48" reading_order_no="48" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">sure that these structures are properly aligned, even if they</text>
<text top="635" left="55" width="205" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t49" reading_order_no="49" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">share no similarity at the primary-structure level.</text>
<text top="659" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t50" reading_order_no="50" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">In addition, we have a weak anchoring option, where con-<i>all </i></text>
<text top="671" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t51" reading_order_no="51" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">sistent anchor points are only used to constraint the out-</text>
<text top="682" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t52" reading_order_no="52" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">put alignment, but are not necessarily aligned to each</text>
<text top="694" left="55" width="241" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t53" reading_order_no="53" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">other. More precisely, if a position x in sequence S i is<i>inconsistent</i></text>
<text top="706" left="55" width="241" height="10" font="font5" id="p1_t54" reading_order_no="54" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">anchored with a position y in sequence S j through one of</text>
<text top="718" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t55" reading_order_no="55" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">the anchor points, this means that y is the only position<a href="">t, see [16] for our</a></text>
<text top="729" left="55" width="241" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t56" reading_order_no="56" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">from S j that can be aligned to x . Whether or not x and y</text>
<text top="87" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t57" reading_order_no="57" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">will actually appear in the same column of the output</text>
<text top="98" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t58" reading_order_no="58" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">alignment depends on the degree of local similarity<i>subset </i></text>
<text top="110" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t59" reading_order_no="59" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">among the sequences around positions x and y . If no sta-</text>
<text top="122" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t60" reading_order_no="60" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">tistically significant similarity can be detected, x and y may</text>
<text top="134" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t61" reading_order_no="61" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">remain un-aligned. Moreover, anchoring x and y means</text>
<text top="145" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t62" reading_order_no="62" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">that positions strictly to the left (or strictly to the right) of</text>
<text top="157" left="313" width="241" height="11" font="font5" id="p1_t63" reading_order_no="63" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">x in S i can be aligned only to positions strictly to the left<i>strong </i></text>
<text top="169" left="313" width="241" height="10" font="font4" id="p1_t64" reading_order_no="64" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">(or strictly to the right) of y in S j – and vice versa. Obvi-</text>
<text top="181" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t65" reading_order_no="65" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">ously, these relations are transitive , so if position x is</text>
<text top="192" left="313" width="242" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t66" reading_order_no="66" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">anchored with position y 1 , y 1 is to the left of another posi-</text>
<text top="204" left="313" width="241" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t67" reading_order_no="67" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">tion y 2 in the same sequence, and y 2 in turn, is aligned to</text>
<text top="216" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t68" reading_order_no="68" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">a position z , then positions to the left of x can be aligned</text>
<text top="228" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t69" reading_order_no="69" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">only to positions to the left of z etc. The 'weak' option may</text>
<text top="239" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t70" reading_order_no="70" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">be useful if anchor points are used to reduce the program</text>
<text top="251" left="313" width="58" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t71" reading_order_no="71" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">running time.</text>
<text top="275" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t72" reading_order_no="72" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Algorithmically, strong or weak anchor points are treated</text>
<text top="286" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t73" reading_order_no="73" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">by DIALIGN in the same way as fragments ( = segment</text>
<text top="298" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t74" reading_order_no="74" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">pairs) in the greedy procedure for multi-alignment. By</text>
<text top="310" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t75" reading_order_no="75" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">transitivity, a set Anc of anchor points defines a quasi par-</text>
<text top="319" left="313" width="78" height="12" font="font5" id="p1_t76" reading_order_no="76" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">tial order relation ≤</text>
<text top="322" left="392" width="162" height="10" font="font4" id="p1_t77" reading_order_no="77" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Anc on the set X of all positions of the</text>
<text top="333" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t78" reading_order_no="78" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">input sequences – in exactly the same way as an alignment<i>weak </i></text>
<text top="342" left="313" width="193" height="12" font="font5" id="p1_t79" reading_order_no="79" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Ali induces a quasi partial order relation ≤</text>
<text top="345" left="506" width="48" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t80" reading_order_no="80" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Ali on X as</text>
<text top="357" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t81" reading_order_no="81" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">described in [16,25]. Formally, we consider an alignment</text>
<text top="369" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t82" reading_order_no="82" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Ali as well as a set of anchor points Anc as an equivalence</text>
<text top="380" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t83" reading_order_no="83" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">relation defined on the set X of all positions of the input<i>x </i></text>
<text top="389" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t84" reading_order_no="84" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">sequences. Next, we consider the partial order relation ≤</text>
<text top="404" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t85" reading_order_no="85" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">on X that is given by the 'natural' ordering of positions<i>S</i></text>
<text top="413" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t86" reading_order_no="86" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">within the sequences. In order-theoretical terms, ≤ is the<i>i </i></text>
<text top="427" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t87" reading_order_no="87" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">direct sum of the linear order relations defined on the indi-</text>
<text top="436" left="313" width="197" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t88" reading_order_no="88" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">vidual sequences. The partial order relation ≤<i>anchored </i></text>
<text top="439" left="511" width="43" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t89" reading_order_no="89" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Anc is then</text>
<text top="448" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t90" reading_order_no="90" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">defined as the transitive closure of the union ≤ ∪ Anc . In<i>y </i></text>
<text top="460" left="313" width="103" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t91" reading_order_no="91" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">other words, we have x ≤</text>
<text top="463" left="416" width="138" height="10" font="font5" id="p1_t92" reading_order_no="92" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Anc y if and only if there is a chain<i>S</i></text>
<text top="474" left="313" width="241" height="11" font="font4" id="p1_t93" reading_order_no="93" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">x 0 , ..., x k of positions with x 0 = x and x k = y such that for<i>j </i></text>
<text top="483" left="313" width="241" height="14" font="font4" id="p1_t94" reading_order_no="94" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">every i ∈ {1,..., k }, position x i -1 is either anchored with x i</text>
<text top="498" left="313" width="241" height="10" font="font4" id="p1_t95" reading_order_no="95" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">or x i -1 and x i belong to the same sequence, and x i -1 is on the</text>
<text top="510" left="313" width="151" height="10" font="font4" id="p1_t96" reading_order_no="96" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">left-hand side of x i in that sequence.<i>y </i></text>
<text top="533" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t97" reading_order_no="97" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">In our set-theoretical setting, a relation R on X is called</text>
<text top="545" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t98" reading_order_no="98" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">consistent if all restrictions of the tansitive closure of the<i>only </i></text>
<text top="554" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t99" reading_order_no="99" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">union ≤ ∪ R to the idividual sequences coincides with their</text>
<text top="568" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t100" reading_order_no="100" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">respective 'natural' linear orderings. With the weak version</text>
<text top="580" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t101" reading_order_no="101" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">of our anchored-alignment approach, we are looking for<i>S</i></text>
<text top="592" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t102" reading_order_no="102" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">an alignment Ali wich maximum score such that the<i>j </i></text>
<text top="601" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t103" reading_order_no="103" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">union Ali ∪ Anc is consistent. With the strong option, we</text>
<text top="615" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t104" reading_order_no="104" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">are looking for a maximum-scoring alignment Ali that is a<i>x</i></text>
<text top="627" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t105" reading_order_no="105" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">superset of Anc . With both program options, our optimi-</text>
<text top="639" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t106" reading_order_no="106" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">sation problem is to find an alignment Ali with maximum<i>x </i></text>
<text top="651" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t107" reading_order_no="107" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">score – under the additional constraint that the set-theo-</text>
<text top="660" left="313" width="241" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t108" reading_order_no="108" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">retical union Ali ∪ Anc is consistent. In the weak anchor-<i>y</i></text>
<text top="674" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t109" reading_order_no="109" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">ing approach, the output alignment is Ali while with the</text>
<text top="686" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t110" reading_order_no="110" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">strong option, the program returns the transitive closure</text>
<text top="695" left="313" width="97" height="12" font="font4" id="p1_t111" reading_order_no="111" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">of the union Ali ∪ Anc .</text>
